quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The Return Type[/h1]

The [b]main [/b]function takes the following general form:[code format="cpp"][b]int [/b]main()
{
  // some code
  return 0;
}[/code]
A function's[b] return type[/b] is declared before its name. In the example above, the return type is [b]int[/b], which indicates that the function returns an integer value.
Occasionally, a function will perform the desired operations without returning a value. Such functions are defined with the keyword [b]void[/b].
[note][b]void [/b]is a basic data type that defines a valueless state.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to define a function named my_func that returns a void and prints "I am a function" in its body:
[!raw!]
{0} my_func()
{
 {1} << "I am a function" << endl;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Defining a Function[/h1]

As an example, let's define a function that does not return a value, and just prints a line of text to the screen.[code format="cpp" ]void printSomething() 
{
  cout << "Hi there!";
}[/code]
Our function, entitled [b]printSomething[/b], returns [b]void[/b], and has no parameters.
Now, we can use our function in [b]main()[/b].[code format="cpp" codeId="231"]int main() 
{
   [b]printSomething()[/b];
   
   return 0;
}[/code]
[note]To [b]call [/b]a function, you simply need to pass the required parameters along with the function name.[/note]

[h1]Functions[/h1]

You must declare a function prior to calling it.
For example: [code format="cpp" codeId="232"]#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void printSomething() {
  cout << "Hi there!";
}

int main() {
  printSomething();

  return 0;
}[/code]
[note]Putting the declaration after the[b] main()[/b] function results in an error.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to print "it works!" on the screen, type in the function prototype before its call.
[!raw!]
void {0}();
int main()
{
  some_func();
  return 0;
}
{1} some_func() {
  cout << "it works!" << endl;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Functions[/h1]

A function [b]declaration[/b], or [b]function prototype[/b], tells the compiler about a function name and how to call the function. The actual body of the function can be defined separately.
[b]For example:[/b] [code format="cpp" codeId="233"]#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

[b]//Function declaration[/b]
void printSomething();

int main() {
  printSomething();

  return 0;
}

[b]//Function definition[/b]
void printSomething() {
  cout << "Hi there!";
}[/code]
[note]Function declaration is required when you define a function in one source file and you call that function in another file. In such case, you should declare the function at the top of the file calling the function.[/note]
